	</p>

	<TableOfContents />

	<h2>Hearing Evaluations</h2>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, we provide comprehensive, diagnostic hearing
		evaluations to give you a clear and accurate picture of your hearing
		health. Our testing process looks closely at how well you hear different
		tones, pitches, and speech sounds, allowing us to identify the type and
		degree of hearing loss you may be experiencing. Because every individual's
		hearing needs are unique, we take the time to explain your results, answer
		your questions, and guide you toward the best next steps.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Which hearing test is the best?">
			<p>
				The best hearing test is the one that matches your personal needs.
				At Commonwealth Audiology, we select the appropriate evaluation
				based on your symptoms, medical history, and listening concerns.
				Our goal is to give you clear answers and a true picture of how
				your hearing is working, so you can move forward with confidence.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can I test my own hearing?">
			<p>
				While online hearing tests and phone apps can be a quick way to get
				a general sense of how you're hearing, they can't match the
				accuracy or detail of a professional evaluation. If you really want
				answers you can trust—and a clear understanding of what's going
				on, a hearing test with an audiologist is the best place to start.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Are online hearing tests any good?">
			<p>
				Online hearing screenings can be a helpful first step, but they
				only tell part of the story. Most simply check whether you can hear
				certain tones through your headphones or speakers, which doesn't
				reflect how you hear in real life conversations.
			</p>
			<p>
				What they can't do is just as important, they can't determine the
				type or cause of hearing loss, measure how well you understand
				speech, or identify any underlying health concerns that may be
				contributing to your symptoms.
			</p>
			<p>
				At Commonwealth Audiology, we take a much more complete approach.
				Our in-depth evaluations are designed to give you a clear, accurate
				understanding of your hearing and guide you toward the next steps
				that are right for you.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Sensorineural Hearing Loss Evaluation &amp; Treatment</h2>
	<p>
		Sensorineural hearing loss is one of the most common types of hearing
		loss. It can make everyday conversations, especially in background noise,
		feel frustrating or exhausting. At Commonwealth Audiology, we take the
		time to truly understand what you're experiencing. Using advanced
		diagnostic tools, we carefully evaluate the health of your inner ear and
		auditory pathways to get a clear picture of your hearing. From there,
		we'll walk through your results together and recommend options tailored
		specifically to your needs and lifestyle. Our goal is simple: to help you
		hear more naturally, communicate with ease, and feel confident in every
		listening environment.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="What are the most common signs of sensorineural hearing loss?">
			<p>
				Sensorineural hearing loss can make speech sound soft, muffled, or
				unclear, especially when there's background noise or more than one
				person talking. You might notice that people seem to be mumbling,
				or that you're turning up the TV louder than you used to.
			</p>
			<p>
				If listening to conversations feels tiring or you're missing parts
				of what's being said, it may be a good idea to schedule a hearing
				evaluation with an audiologist.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How is sensorineural hearing loss diagnosed?">
			<p>
				Sensorineural hearing loss is identified through a comprehensive
				hearing evaluation made up of several different tests. At
				Commonwealth Audiology, we use a combination of advanced
				assessments to evaluate how your inner ear and auditory pathways
				respond to sound. Together, these results allow us to confirm
				whether the hearing loss is sensorineural in nature and understand
				its type and severity. From there, we can recommend the most
				effective solutions tailored to your needs.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="What treatment options are available for sensorineural hearing loss?">
			<p>
				While sensorineural hearing loss can't be reversed, there are many
				effective ways to help you hear more clearly and feel more
				connected in everyday life. Treatment options may include
				professionally fitted hearing aids, assistive listening devices, or
				simple, personalized strategies that make listening easier in the
				situations you find most challenging.
			</p>
			<p>
				We take the time to understand your needs and lifestyle so we can
				create a care plan that feels right for you, helping you hear with
				greater comfort, confidence, and ease each day.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Ear Wax Removal</h2>
	<p>
		Excess ear wax can cause that uncomfortable fullness, itching, and even
		temporary hearing loss. The good news is, it's an easy fix. Our goal is to
		always provide safe, gentle ear wax removal using professional tools that
		protect your ears (no cotton swabs needed!). If you're experiencing
		blockage, itching, or a sudden drop in hearing, our trained audiologist
		can help you find quick and comfortable relief.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Is it safe to remove ear wax at home?">
			<p>
				It's natural to want quick relief when your ears feel blocked, but
				trying to remove ear wax at home, especially with cotton swabs, ear
				candles, or other objects, can actually make things worse. These
				methods can push wax deeper, irritate the ear canal, or even cause
				injury.
			</p>
			<p>
				The safest option is professional care. At Commonwealth Audiology,
				we use gentle, effective techniques to safely remove ear wax and
				protect the health of your ears.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How do I know if I need professional ear wax removal?">
			<p>
				If your ears feel full, your hearing sounds muffled, or you're
				dealing with itching or sudden blockage, excess ear wax may be the
				cause. Some people also notice ringing in the ears or mild
				discomfort. A quick, comfortable evaluation at Commonwealth
				Audiology can confirm whether wax is the issue and provide
				immediate relief.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How often should I have my ears cleaned?">
			<p>
				It really depends on your individual ears. Some people naturally
				produce more ear wax. Hearing aids can also lead to faster buildup.
				Others may rarely need cleaning at all. Our audiologist can
				evaluate your ears and recommend a personalized schedule that fits
				your needs, helping keep your ears clear, comfortable, and healthy
				year-round.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Tinnitus Evaluations and Treatment</h2>
	<p>
		If you're dealing with ringing, buzzing, or humming in your ears, it can
		be frustrating, distracting, and even exhausting, and you're definitely
		not alone. At Commonwealth Audiology, we take the time to listen and
		understand how tinnitus is affecting your day-to-day life. Through a
		thorough evaluation, we look at what might be contributing, whether it's
		changes in hearing, noise exposure, stress, or other underlying factors.
		From there, we'll walk through personalized, evidence-based options
		together, focused on helping you find relief and feel more in control
		again.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Should I go to an audiologist for tinnitus?">
			<p>
				Yes, if you're dealing with ringing, buzzing, or humming in your
				ears, you don't have to figure it out alone. Audiologists are
				trained to help understand what's causing tinnitus and how it may
				be connected to your hearing health.
			</p>
			<p>
				At Commonwealth Audiology, we take the time to really listen to
				what you're experiencing, look for possible triggers, and check
				whether hearing loss may be playing a role. From there, we'll walk
				you through personalized options that can help reduce the impact of
				tinnitus and make day-to-day life feel more comfortable again.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Is tinnitus a brain problem?">
			<p>
				Tinnitus usually starts with changes in the ear, but the brain is
				involved too. When the ear isn't sending as many sound signals,
				often because of hearing loss, the brain can "fill in the gaps" by
				creating its own sound, like ringing or buzzing.
			</p>
			<p>
				That's why treatment often focuses on both the ears and the brain.
				Options like ear level tinnitus maskers, sound therapy, and
				counseling can help retrain how your brain responds to sound,
				making tinnitus less noticeable and easier to manage over time.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="What happens if tinnitus is not treated?">
			<p>
				If tinnitus isn't addressed, it can become more frustrating over
				time. Many people notice it starts to interfere with sleep, makes
				it harder to concentrate, or adds extra stress to their day. If
				hearing loss is also present, conversations may become even more
				challenging.
			</p>
			<p>
				The good news is that you don't have to just live with it. Getting
				help early can make a real difference in how much tinnitus affects
				your daily life. At Commonwealth Audiology, we're here to support
				you in finding relief and getting back to feeling more comfortable
				and in control.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Hearing Aid Services</h2>
	<p>
		Getting hearing aids is a big step, but it's really just the start of your
		journey. As you adjust, questions come up, sounds feel different, and your
		needs may change, and that's completely normal. At Commonwealth Audiology,
		we're here for all of it. From personalized fittings and fine-tuning to
		repairs and routine maintenance, we'll make sure your hearing aids
		continue to feel comfortable and work the way you need them to in your
		everyday life. You're not on your own, we're with you every step of the
		way.
	</p>

	<h2>Hearing Aid Fittings</h2>
	<p>
		A well-fit hearing aid can truly change the way you experience sound. We
		take the time to carefully program and fine-tune your devices using
		real-ear measurements and personalized adjustments tailored just for you.
		Our goal is simple, to help your hearing aids sound as natural and clear
		as possible, so you can feel more confident, comfortable, and connected in
		the moments that matter most.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="How long does it take to get fitted for a hearing aid?">
			<p>
				A hearing aid fitting typically takes about an hour. During this
				visit, we make sure your hearing aids feel comfortable and sound
				right for you. We'll walk you through how everything works, talk
				about what to realistically expect, and go over helpful tips like a
				wear schedule to make your adjustment easier.
			</p>
			<p>
				We also take time to show you how to properly insert, remove, and
				care for your devices so you feel confident using them at home.
				After your fitting, our team will schedule follow-up visits to
				fine-tune your settings and make sure you continue to adjust
				comfortably and hear your best.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How does an audiologist fit a hearing aid?">
			<p>
				Using your hearing test results, we program your hearing aids to
				match your specific hearing needs. We then make sure the physical
				fit is comfortable and secure, and we'll show you exactly how to
				insert, remove, clean, and care for your devices so you feel
				confident using them every day.
			</p>
			<p>
				During your trial period, we'll see you back several times to
				fine-tune your settings and make sure everything is working as it
				should. To do that, we use precise real-ear measurements, which
				allow us to confirm that the hearing aids are delivering the right
				amount of amplification for your unique ear canal.
			</p>
			<p>
				This is considered the gold standard in audiology, and an important
				step in making sure you're getting the best possible hearing
				outcome.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can you get a hearing aid without a test?">
			<p>
				Over-The-Counter (OTC) hearing aids can be purchased without a
				hearing test, while prescription hearing aids require one. Beyond
				that difference, OTC devices do not include the personalized
				programming, fine-tuning, or ongoing professional support that come
				with audiology care.
			</p>
			<p>
				At Commonwealth Audiology, we recommend starting with a
				comprehensive hearing evaluation. This helps us understand your
				unique hearing needs, match you with the most appropriate solution,
				and make sure there are no underlying medical concerns affecting
				your hearing.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Hearing Aid Repairs and Cleaning</h2>
	<p>
		Your hearing aids are with you through so many important moments every
		day, and just like anything you rely on, they need a little care along the
		way. We're here to make that easy for you. Whether it's a routine
		cleaning, a quick adjustment, or a repair that can't wait, we'll take care
		of it so your devices stay comfortable, clear, and working their best. If
		something isn't sounding right, we'll help get you back on track as
		quickly as possible, so you don't miss a beat.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="What are the common problems that require hearing aid repair?">
			<p>
				Hearing aids are with you throughout your day, so it's normal for
				small issues to come up from time to time. The most common problems
				include weak or no sound, distorted or unclear audio, whistling or
				feedback, and physical wear or damage. If something doesn't seem
				right, our team is here to help take a closer look and get your
				devices back to working the way they should.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How long does it take to repair a hearing aid?">
			<p>
				Repair time really depends on what's going on. Many smaller issues,
				like cleaning, replacing filters, or changing minor parts, can often
				be taken care of right in our office, sometimes the same day. If
				your hearing aids need to be sent to the manufacturer for more
				complex repairs, it may take a few days to a couple of weeks. Either
				way, we'll keep you updated and make sure you know exactly what to
				expect along the way.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can I fix my hearing aid at home?">
			<p>
				There are a few simple things you can try at home, like checking
				the battery, cleaning the microphone or receiver openings, or
				replacing a wax filter. These quick steps can often solve minor
				issues. If that doesn't do the trick, it's best to let us take a
				look. We're here to help troubleshoot the problem, protect your
				devices, and make sure you're hearing your best again as quickly as
				possible.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

	<h2>Hearing Protection</h2>
	<p>
		Whether you're playing music, out in the field, working in a loud
		environment, or just regularly around high noise levels, protecting your
		hearing matters more than most people realize. It's easy to brush off loud
		sounds in the moment, but over time, they can add up. At Commonwealth
		Audiology, we offer custom-fit ear protection designed specifically for
		you. These solutions help lower harmful noise while still letting you hear
		what you need to, so you can keep doing what you love, safely and
		comfortably, for years to come.
	</p>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="What types of hearing protection are best for everyday loud environments?">
			<p>
				The best hearing protection really depends on what kinds of sounds
				you're around and how often you're exposed to them. For occasional
				loud situations, earplugs or earmuffs can work well. But if you're
				regularly in noisy environments, custom-molded hearing protection
				offers the most comfortable and consistent fit. We create custom
				solutions that help protect your hearing while still allowing you
				to stay aware of important sounds around you, so you don't have to
				choose between safety and staying connected.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Why do musicians need specialized hearing protection?">
			<p>
				For musicians, sound is everything, but repeated exposure to high
				volume levels can take a toll on your hearing over time. While
				standard earplugs can muffle and distort sound, making it hard to
				hear pitch and detail, custom musician earplugs are designed
				differently. They reduce volume evenly across frequencies, so the
				music still sounds natural, just at a safer level. At Commonwealth
				Audiology, we help musicians protect their hearing without
				sacrificing the clarity and quality they rely on to perform at
				their best.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How does hearing protection help hunters and shooters?">
			<p>
				Gunfire is extremely loud, and even a single exposure can cause
				lasting hearing damage. That's why proper protection is so important
				for hunters and shooting sports enthusiasts. The right hearing
				protection lowers harmful noise levels while still letting you hear
				important sounds like movement, conversation, and what's happening
				around you in the field. We offer custom-fit options designed for
				comfort, safety, and awareness, so you can enjoy your time outdoors
				while protecting your hearing for the long run.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>
</InternalPage>
